  • 2005-02-28 17:25:42

    Make the file writable

    Make the config.inc.php file writable by right clicking on it and choosing properties, then unchecking read only or archive check box, before you start the install. Do the same for the content directory you create, so it too can be written to.

    This problem seems to be specific to Win 2003/IIS systems.

    Try using an Apache webserver if you can install one, or have access to one. It is more stable that IIS for running PHP.

  • 2005-07-12 08:13:31

    safemode off

    I'll guess that lastest means 1.5RC3. Safe-mode needs to be turned off. Chance are your ISP has it turned on. Register_globals also has to be turned off. Create a phpinfo page to see your php settings. Cretae file with the following content, then open it in your browser.

    <?php
    phpinfo();
    ?>

    Be sure the php version is at least 4.2.

    Also check what web server is being used. If its on a WINXP system, chances are it is IIS, which is not very stable with PHP.

  • 2005-07-12 08:45:33

    IIS vs Apache

    Running ATutor on an Apache system with PHP enable is by far the more stable configuration. There have been a variety of issues reported on IIS systems, which we are not able to deal with (we don't maintain an IIS server). While in principle ATutor should run on IIS, in reality IIS leaves much to be desired for running PHP.

    If you have an opportunity, move on to an Apache based system. You'll likely experience other problems if you continue on an IIS system (assuming you can get ATutor installed after getting register-global turned off). Your ISP should be warned that leaving it turned on presents security issues.

  • 2005-07-18 22:48:04

    possible solution to blank PHP pages

    I have noticed many forums on the internet where users seem to be mystified by the blank php page that shows up when they test the following code (or any php code mixed with HTML);

    <html>
    <head>
    <title>Test PHP</title>
    </head>

    <body>
    <?php
    phpinfo ( );
    ?>

    </body>
    </html>

    The blank PHP pages are occurring because the users are attempting to write their code using an some editor that is not coding in plain text. The users are coding in text that contains HTML itself. WordPad was giving me this trouble. Once I copied and pasted my code written in WordPad (incorporates HTML features into text) into NotePad (strictly plain text) and WALLAH... when I accessed my phpinfo test page I no longer saw a blank page. Before I used notepad, when I would "view source" while visiting the blank web page I would see the following sorta tags and HTML;

    <!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN">
    <HTML><HEAD>
    <META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"></HEAD>
    <BODY></BODY></HTML>

    If you wish to use WordPad, then you must save the file as a text document (.txt) instead of the default RichText format which allows the use of HTML formatting behind the scenes.

    Sincerely,
    Shawn Englerth

    Re: Have same problem

    I faced this problem before. This issue is related to connecting to the database.
    To reslove this problem open "include/vitals.inc.php" go to line 121, remove the @ from mysql_connect. The related error will appear, make sure to set display_errors to ON in php.ini, and comment all error_reporting(0) from you code to be able to view the errors.
